Document:  [Migrating Confluence Between Servers|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Migrating+Confluence+Between+Servers]

Need to review: 
1.  {quote}Modify the location of your war file if need be. If using Tomcat, this is likely in /Conf/Catalina/localhost. You'll want to make sure the docbase attribute is pointing to the right location.{quote}
Note: we should mentioned that this is only for WAR installation.

2. {quote}Use a database administration tool to confirm that the user can login from the localhost.{quote}
Note: this one can be remove, as the DB might not be on the same server

3.{quote}This step depends on your database connection:
If you use JDBC (the default option) to connect to the database, to modify any database connection information, go to the Confluence home directory and edit confluence.cfg.xml. The connection URL is set under hibernate.connection.url. Ensure it does not point to your production database server.
If you use a data source, follow the instructions for your database type and ensure the data source points to the new database: PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQL Server or Oracle.{quote}

Note: this is needed when Confluence and DB are running on two different servers or the connection URL is using Hostname rather then localhost

4. {quote}If you are using internal user management, skip this step.{quote}
Note: need more detail how can we identify whether we are using internal user management

5. {quote}If appropriate, make sure no emails are sent out from the test system.{quote}
Note: specified that only for the mail server and give more explanation on the SQL output, for example what it means if the query return empty row.

